This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it proposes a new framework for multi-output Gaussian processes using a convolutional spectral mixture kernel. It also mentions extensive experiments on synthetic and real datasets, which is a common practice in machine learning research. Additionally, the paper may also be relevant to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as it deals with modeling channel dependencies and pattern extrapolation. The use of spectral mixtures also suggests a potential application in computer vision (cs.CV) and signal processing (cs.ST). Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category as it deals with modeling correlations between different channels.
